Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

Alex, I don't think maintaining all links in the linkEA should be a requirement, since this would limit the total link count on the file too much.  I think it is fine if "lfs fid2path" does not return all of the links to a file, since a few pathnames are typically enough to know what file a FID is.  Otherwise, we would have a severe limitation on the number of hard links we could create on a file.

I tried to go through and clean up the code to have linkea_init() and linkea_links_find() return -ENODATA when leh_reccount == 0, but there are some callers that want this, and others that don't.  I think it makes sense to have a wrapper function that has the leh_reccount == 0 check, so that it isn't splattered all over the code, and remove the leh_reccount and added leh_overflow_time from linkea_init().  The latter check was added so that LFSCK could still read the linkEA even if it is empty, but it is not needed if linkea_init() always returns only the structure and doesn't try to return -ENODATA.  

int linkea_init_with_rec(struct linkea_data *ldata)
{
       int rc;

       rc = linkea_init(ldata);

       if (rc == 0 && ldata->ld_leh->leh_reccount == 0)
               rc = -ENODATA;

       return rc;
}
EXPORT_SYMBOL(linkea_init_with_rec);

Then, the callers of linkea_init() need to be checked to decide whether they want the ENODATA behaviour or not (I suspect most do, except for LFSCK that needs access to leh_overflow_time even when the linkEA is empty.
